<taxonomicName authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[281,488,1444,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shangui" status="gen. et sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[281,488,1444,1468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva shangui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[494,626,1445,1469]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[494,626,1445,1469]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="species">
gen. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[545,563,1445,1468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">et</emphasis>
sp. n.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, male, photographed in the field, Xinglong, China (Photograph copyright: Shan Gui). (Link: https://www.inaturalist.org/photos/54918804)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1551,1937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
The lack of a hind coxal knob is exceedingly rare in 
<taxonomicName box="[774,903,1551,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Therevidae</taxonomicName>
, being absent only in a few species in the genera 
<taxonomicName box="[151,326,1587,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Anabarhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,326,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Anabarhynchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Krober" authorityName="Krober" authorityYear="1912" box="[339,532,1587,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Actorthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[339,445,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Actorthia</emphasis>
Kröber
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Irwin &amp; Lyneborg" authorityYear="1981" box="[541,673,1587,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Ammonaios" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[541,673,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Ammonaios</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Irwin &amp; Lyneborg" authorityName="Irwin &amp; Lyneborg" authorityYear="1981" box="[725,1047,1587,1613]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Arenigena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[725,841,1587,1613]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Arenigena</emphasis>
Irwin &amp; Lyneborg
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hauser, M. &amp; Irwin, M. E." box="[1062,1307,1587,1613]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="738 - 765" refId="ref3102" refString="Hauser, M. &amp; Irwin, M. E. (2003) The Nearctic genus Ammonaios Irwin &amp; Lyneborg, 1981 (Diptera: Therevidae). Annals of the American Entomological Society, 96, 738 - 765." type="journal article" year="2003">Hauser &amp; Irwin, 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Winterton, S. L." pageId="2" pageNumber="363" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref3264" refString="Winterton, S. L. (2004) Are hind coxal knobs a synapomorphy for therevids?: An unusual new species of Anabarhynchus Macquart from Australia (Diptera: Therevidae: Therevinae). Zootaxa, 413, 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="2004">Winterton, 2004</bibRefCitation>
). The apparent distant relationship amongst many of these genera suggests that loss of the hind coxal knob has occurred multiple times.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1551,1937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
Remarkably, while wasp mimicry is found in other stiletto flies, it typically takes the form of mimicking pompilid or sphecid wasps (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authority="Guerin" authorityName="Guerin" box="[472,710,1731,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Agapophytus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[472,618,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Agapophytus</emphasis>
Guerin
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[729,960,1731,1757]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shangui" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[729,960,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva shangui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[968,1033,1731,1757]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[968,1033,1731,1757]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is the first example of a stiletto fly that apparently mimics bees (
<taxonomicName box="[479,566,1767,1794]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Apidae</taxonomicName>
), resembling species of bumble bees in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="L. Indeed" authorityName="L. Indeed" box="[1124,1331,1767,1793]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1214,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Bombus</emphasis>
L. Indeed
</taxonomicName>
, this new stiletto fly is very similar to species such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1781" box="[642,965,1803,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sibiricus">
<emphasis box="[642,835,1803,1829]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Bombus sibiricus</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1002,1213,1803,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Bombus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hypnorum">
<emphasis box="[1002,1213,1803,1829]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Bombus hypnorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.), which are also found in the same area. Still, while the erect vestiture and bee-like mimicking appearance is distinctive for 
<taxonomicName authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shangui" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva shangui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[316,380,1875,1901]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[316,380,1875,1901]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, it is possible that these features are species-specific and not characteristic of the genus. Only when more species are discovered, may the full extent of such mimicry in 
<taxonomicName authority="Winterton, 2020" authorityName="Winterton" authorityYear="2020" box="[985,1118,1911,1937]" class="Insecta" family="Therevidae" genus="Sinothereva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[985,1118,1911,1937]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="363">Sinothereva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1124,1200,1911,1937]" pageId="2" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
be known.
</paragraph>
